Transit Oriented Displacement? Has Minnesota’s Green Line Propagated Gentrification?

Brian Pryzby

November 16, 2023

Group Members and Contribution

At this point, all work as been done by myself with the intention of merging paths with Gugo following the completion of this presentation

Research Question and Motivation

Has the Twin Cities’ Green Line light rail line contributed to gentrification of the surrounding areas? I seek to answer this question using change in four primary indicators between 2013 and 2019, mean property value, median household income, poverty, and percentage white population. I also explore changes in public transit usage to further contextualize the impact of the line. This question was inspired by knowledge of significant development plans along University Ave which are concurrent with the development of the Green Line, such as Allianz Field and “gentrification building” style housing developments in Prospect Park and at the intersection of Hamline and University. The length of University Ave has long been home to a diverse working class community, and I seek to explore if the Green Line has kick-started the process of gentrifying this area.

ramsey13pivot <- ramsey13 %>% 
  select(-"moe") %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "variable", values_from = "estimate") %>% 
  group_by("NAME") 

ramsey13clean <-  ramsey13pivot %>% 
  mutate(whitePerc13 = popWhite/popTotal) %>% 
  mutate(transitPerc13 = transitUsage/transitTotal) %>% 
  mutate(povertyPerc13 = povertyUnder/povertyTotal) 

hennepin13pivot <- hennepin13 %>% 
  select(-"moe") %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "variable", values_from = "estimate") %>% 
  group_by("NAME") 

hennepin13clean <-  hennepin13pivot %>% 
  mutate(whitePerc13 = popWhite/popTotal) %>% 
  mutate(transitPerc13 = transitUsage/transitTotal) %>% 
  mutate(povertyPerc13 = povertyUnder/povertyTotal) 

ramsey19pivot <- ramsey19 %>% 
  select(-"moe") %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "variable", values_from = "estimate") %>% 
  group_by("NAME") 

ramsey19clean <-  ramsey19pivot %>% 
  mutate(whitePerc19 = popWhite/popTotal) %>% 
  mutate(transitPerc19 = transitUsage/transitTotal) %>% 
  mutate(povertyPerc19 = povertyUnder/povertyTotal) %>% 
  st_drop_geometry()

hennepin19pivot <- hennepin19 %>% 
  select(-"moe") %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "variable", values_from = "estimate") %>% 
  group_by("NAME") 

hennepin19clean <-  hennepin19pivot %>% 
  mutate(whitePerc19 = popWhite/popTotal) %>% 
  mutate(transitPerc19 = transitUsage/transitTotal) %>% 
  mutate(povertyPerc19 = povertyUnder/povertyTotal) %>% 
  st_drop_geometry()

ramsey <- left_join(x=ramsey13clean, y=ramsey19clean, by="GEOID")
hennepin <- left_join(x=hennepin13clean, y=hennepin19clean, by="GEOID")
  
ramsey <- ramsey %>% 
  mutate(whiteChange = whitePerc19 - whitePerc13) %>% 
  mutate(transitChange = transitPerc19 - transitPerc13) %>% 
  mutate(povertyChange = povertyPerc19 - povertyPerc13) %>% 
  mutate(incomeChange = income.y - income.x) %>% 
  mutate(propertyValueChange = propertyValue.y - propertyValue.x)

hennepin <- hennepin  %>% 
  mutate(whiteChange = whitePerc19 - whitePerc13) %>% 
  mutate(transitChange = transitPerc19 - transitPerc13) %>% 
  mutate(povertyChange = povertyPerc19 - povertyPerc13) %>% 
  mutate(incomeChange = income.y - income.x) %>% 
  mutate(propertyValueChange = propertyValue.y - propertyValue.x)

bothCounties <- rbind(hennepin, ramsey)

I use the dataset above for my analysis, which contains variables from the 5-year ACS queried from the official Census API. I focus on median household income, mean property value, poverty, % white population and reliance on public transportation. Data is gathered at the block group aggregation and is compared between 2013 and 2019 measurements.

White Percentage Change (Intersected Blocks vs. All): -0.25% vs. -3.01% Transit Usage Change (Intersected Blocks vs. All): 1.67% vs. -0.12% Poverty Change (Intersected Blocks vs. All): -5.70% vs. -2.63% $ Income Change (Intersected Blocks vs. All): 14,064 vs. 14,926 $ Property Value Change (Intersected Blocks vs. All): 42,556 vs. 41,371

I have not yet produced a way to statistically interpret these values/differences. For now I am simply remarking on what I believe are noticeable differences. There seems to be significant gaps between the change in both white population and poverty between Green Line adjacent block groups and the rest of the Twin Cities, with a greater rate of poverty decrease and smaller rate of white population decrease near the line, both potential signs of gentrification. This, however, is negated by a lower rate of income change and a negligibly higher rate of property value change. It is interesting, as well, to note that there is an increase in transit usage near the Green Line while overall usage decreases across the Twin Cities. This is not entirely a surprise though at least it validates the effectiveness of the development.
